wiki_catalogs.name: Introduction
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the introduction section focused on the Woby framework. Explain its purpose as a high-performance, observable-based reactive framework for building rich web applications. Highlight its core architectural principles including no VDOM, automatic dependency tracking, and direct DOM manipulation. Discuss the benefits of its minimal dependencies and lack of Babel transforms. Provide a high-level overview of how Woby differs from React-like frameworks, emphasizing its unique features such as advanced nested property support and built-in class management. Include key use cases and target applications. Document the relationship between Woby and its reactive core Soby. Use terminology consistent with the codebase like observables, signals, and reactivity. Include practical examples from the README showing basic component structure and rendering patterns.

wiki_catalogs.name: Observable-Based Reactivity
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the observable-based reactivity system in Woby. Explain how the $() function creates fine-grained signals and enables automatic dependency tracking without dependency arrays. Detail the underlying soby engine and its integration with Woby's rendering system. Describe how observables automatically resolve in mathematical operations and support type options for HTML attribute synchronization. Include practical examples showing observable creation with type annotations (number, boolean, object) and custom equality functions. Document the role of $$() for safely unwrapping values and handling both observable and plain values. Explain how this reactivity model eliminates stale closures and enables automatic re-execution of effects. Address performance benefits over traditional state-based frameworks and integration with custom elements.

wiki_catalogs.name: State Management
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the State Management sub-feature focused on Woby's observable-based state system. Explain how use_state and related hooks leverage soby observables for fine-grained reactivity without dependency arrays. Document the implementation in soby.ts and use_resolved.ts for automatic dependency tracking. Include examples of creating and updating reactive state, handling nested properties, and integrating with components. Illustrate how state changes trigger precise DOM updates without VDOM. Address common issues such as stale closures and over-disposal, and provide solutions. Highlight performance benefits of granular reactivity and best practices for structuring state in large applications.

wiki_catalogs.name: Dynamic Components
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the Dynamic component in Woby. Explain its purpose in enabling runtime component resolution and lazy loading. Document the implementation differences between client (dynamic.ts), server-side rendering (dynamic.ssr.ts), and via.js (dynamic.via.ts) environments. Include interface definitions, props such as 'component' and 'props', and behavior during hydration. Provide practical examples showing dynamic component switching based on state or user interaction. Address integration with lazy loading via `lazy()` and error handling during resolution. Discuss performance implications and best practices for code-splitting. Cover common issues like SSR hydration mismatches and how to resolve them using proper loading states.

wiki_catalogs.name: Browser Rendering
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for Woby's browser rendering implementation in render.ts. Explain the rendering pipeline, including how components are mounted, updated, and unmounted directly to the DOM without a virtual DOM. Document the reactive update mechanism using fine-grained observables and how changes propagate efficiently to the DOM via setters. Describe the role of the render() function, its parameters (component, container), and lifecycle integration. Include code examples showing basic and advanced rendering scenarios. Explain integration with JSX via jsx-runtime and the h() function. Address performance considerations such as minimal re-renders, direct DOM manipulation benefits, and memory management. Discuss common issues like stale references or timing issues with microtasks and provide solutions.

Provide concrete examples from the codebase showing conditional class application, array-based class composition, and object-driven class toggling. Illustrate integration with components and JSX, demonstrating real-world usage patterns. Address common issues such as class duplication, performance bottlenecks with large class sets, and solutions for ensuring idempotent updates. Include performance optimization tips, such as minimizing re-renders and leveraging fine-grained reactivity to avoid unnecessary DOM operations.

Explain useAbortController and useAbortSignal for managing cancellation tokens in asynchronous operations. Cover useAnimationFrame and useAnimationLoop for animation timing with automatic cleanup. Document useContext for consuming context values with proper typing and default value handling. Explain useEventListener for declarative event binding with automatic disposal. Detail useFetch for declarative HTTP requests with built-in abort control and reactivity. Cover useResource for managing async resources with pending/error/resolved states. Include usePromise for tracking promise states. Document timing hooks (useTimeout, useInterval) with cleanup behavior. Provide examples showing dependency-free reactivity, proper disposal patterns, and integration with observable state.

wiki_catalogs.name: Resource and Data Fetching Hooks
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for Woby's resource management hooks. Explain use_resource for declaratively managing async resources with pending, error, and resolved states. Cover use_fetch for reactive HTTP requests with built-in abort control via useAbortController. Document use_promise for tracking promise state transitions. Include use_resolved for synchronizing with resolved values in suspense-compatible workflows. Provide examples for data loading, caching strategies, and error handling. Address cancellation patterns using AbortSignal, and demonstrate integration with Suspense boundaries. Highlight how these hooks automatically re-run on dependency changes without explicit dependency arrays.

wiki_catalogs.name: List Rendering
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the For component used in list rendering. Explain its role in efficiently rendering arrays with automatic diffing and keyed updates using Woby's observable system. Document the props interface including 'each' (observable array), 'children' render function with item/index, 'key' accessor, and memoization options. Describe how it avoids VDOM by directly manipulating DOM nodes and tracking changes at the item level. Include examples of todo lists, data tables, and infinite scroll implementations. Highlight performance optimizations such as recycling DOM nodes, minimizing layout thrashing, and handling large datasets. Address edge cases like duplicate keys, async updates, and integration with useResource for paginated data. Compare with manual map() patterns and explain when For provides superior reactivity.

wiki_catalogs.name: Hyperscript Utilities
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create detailed documentation for the h() function and html utilities. Explain h() as the JSX compilation target that delegates to createElement() with proper argument normalization. Document how it handles children in props vs rest parameters, and its role in the JSX transformation pipeline. Cover the html.ts variants that provide tag registry support for shorthand element creation. Include examples of JSX compilation output and manual h() usage. Explain the differences between standard, SSR, and via.js implementations, and how they maintain compatibility across rendering targets. Address usage patterns, performance implications, and integration with JSX tooling.

wiki_catalogs.name: Ternary Component
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for Woby's Ternary component. Explain its purpose as a lightweight conditional rendering primitive that selects between two children based on a condition, analogous to the JavaScript ternary operator. Document how it takes a 'when' observable and an array of two children (true/false branches), using the internal ternary utility for efficient switching. Describe its minimal overhead and direct implementation that makes it ideal for simple conditional logic. Provide usage examples such as toggling classes, showing/hiding elements, and inline conditional rendering. Highlight its role as the foundation for other conditional components like If. Include code examples showing both JSX and programmatic usage, and compare its performance characteristics with the If component for simple boolean conditions.

wiki_catalogs.name: Via.js Rendering
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Document the Via.js-specific rendering pipeline in render.via.ts. Explain how this implementation integrates with the via.js runtime for optimized rendering performance. Highlight differences from the standard browser renderer, including the simplified setter system (setters.via) and compatibility constraints. Detail the render() function's parameter requirements and disposal mechanism. Provide an example demonstrating how to use Via.js rendering for high-performance applications. Discuss use cases where Via.js integration provides advantages, such as reduced bundle size or improved execution speed. Address limitations and compatibility requirements when using this rendering target.

wiki_catalogs.name: Via.js Proxy-Based Element Creation
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed documentation for createElement() when integrated with via.js for proxy-based reactivity. Explain how it creates elements that work seamlessly with via.js's transparent reactivity system, including the use of IsSvgSymbol for SVG detection and IgnoreSymbols to prevent proxy interference. Document the streamlined property setting via setters.via and child assignment without FragmentUtils, optimized for proxy-based updates. Highlight differences from standard implementation, such as simplified stack usage with Error objects and direct return of proxied elements. Provide examples of creating reactive components that automatically update via.js proxies. Address integration challenges, including proper symbol handling, avoiding infinite loops in proxies, and ensuring compatibility with via.js's reactivity model. Include performance benefits of direct proxy integration and best practices for hybrid rendering scenarios.

wiki_catalogs.name: Via.js Integration
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Document the lazy() function's implementation for the Via.js runtime environment. Explain how it interfaces with Via.js's unique rendering model and event loop integration. Highlight the use of create_element.via for proper element creation within the Via.js context and how asynchronous resolution is synchronized with Via.js's execution flow. Describe scenarios where Via.js integration provides performance benefits for lazy loading, such as in micro-frontend architectures or when integrating with other JavaScript runtimes. Provide usage examples showing lazy loading of components in Via.js-powered applications and address any limitations or special configuration requirements when using lazy loading across runtime boundaries.

wiki_catalogs.name: Nested Property Handling
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for nested property support in Woby custom elements. Explain how properties with $ or . notation (e.g., nested$prop$value or nested.prop.value) are automatically detected and processed. Document the normalizePropertyPath utility that standardizes property paths, and the setNestedProperty function that handles both general nested objects and style-specific properties. Detail how style properties (style$font-size or style.font-size) are converted from kebab-case to camelCase and applied to the element's style object. Cover the differences between HTML and JSX usage patterns, and explain how nested observables are updated through setObservableValue. Include practical examples of complex nested data structures and address common issues like path parsing errors and type coercion in nested contexts.

wiki_catalogs.name: Components
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the components section focused on Woby's built-in UI components. Explain the purpose and usage of each component including Dynamic, If, For, Portal, Suspense, and ErrorBoundary. Document their props, behavior, and integration patterns. Provide practical examples from the codebase showing how to use conditional rendering, list rendering, and dynamic component loading. Explain the differences between client and SSR implementations (e.g., portal.ts vs portal.ssr.ts). Cover advanced features like keep-alive and ternary components. Include guidance on when to use each component and performance considerations. Address common issues and best practices for component composition.

wiki_catalogs.name: Timing Functions
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the Timing Functions sub-feature focused on time-based operations in Woby. Explain how use_timeout, use_interval, and other timing hooks integrate with the reactivity system and are automatically cleaned up on component disposal. Document the implementation of animation frame, idle callback, and microtask scheduling hooks. Include practical examples such as debounced inputs, polling, animations, and background processing. Highlight how these hooks prevent common memory leaks by tying their lifecycle to components. Address performance considerations for high-frequency updates and provide optimization strategies for animation and idle work. Show integration patterns with other hooks like use_resource for polling implementations.

wiki_catalogs.name: Portals
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create detailed documentation for the Portal component in Woby. Explain its purpose in rendering children into a DOM node outside the parent components hierarchy, commonly used for modals, tooltips, and overlays. Document the implementation across environments: client (portal.ts), SSR (portal.ssr.ts), and via.js (portal.via.ts). Describe how portals maintain reactivity and event bubbling across boundaries. Provide usage examples including mounting modals in document.body and managing focus. Address hydration challenges in SSR where target containers may not exist initially. Discuss cleanup strategies and memory management when portals are unmounted. Include troubleshooting tips for common issues like style isolation, z-index conflicts, and event propagation.

wiki_catalogs.name: Types and Interfaces
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive documentation for Woby's type system and interfaces. Detail the Component type union encompassing functions, intrinsic elements, and DOM nodes. Explain the Child type hierarchy supporting null, primitives, nodes, observables, and render functions. Document the Props interface for component properties with JSX compatibility. Cover Observable<T> and ObservableReadonly<T> interfaces from the soby reactivity system. Explain Resource<T> type for async data loading with pending/error/resolved states. Detail CSSProperties and Style types for type-safe styling with function values. Document EventTarget-specific event handlers with proper typing. Cover Ref and Refs types for DOM references. Explain the Directive system types including DirectiveFunction, DirectiveRef, and DirectiveProvider. Include examples of type usage in components and hooks, and document advanced patterns like conditional typing and generics in the type system.

wiki_catalogs.name: Event and Timing Hooks
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for Woby's event and timing hooks. Explain use_event_listener for declarative DOM event binding with automatic cleanup on unmount. Cover timing hooks: use_timeout and use_interval for delayed or repeated execution with disposal guarantees. Document animation-focused hooks: use_animation_frame and use_animation_loop for smooth 60fps updates. Include use_idle_callback and use_idle_loop for background task scheduling using the IdleDeadline API. Explain use_microtask for post-render asynchronous operations. Cover use_scheduler for advanced scheduling control. Provide examples for gesture handling, polling, animation loops, and performance-sensitive background work. Emphasize automatic disposal and integration with component lifecycle.

wiki_catalogs.name: Portal
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the Portal component. Explain its purpose in rendering children into a DOM node outside the parent component's hierarchy, commonly used for modals, tooltips, and popovers. Document the 'mount' prop for target selection (selector string, Element, or function) and default behavior using document.body. Describe event bubbling across portal boundaries and how Woby preserves normal event propagation semantics. Cover SSR considerations in portal.ssr.ts including hydration matching and deferred mounting. Explain via.js integration in portal.via.ts for alternative rendering environments. Provide examples of accessible modals with focus trapping, tooltip positioning, and nested portals. Address styling encapsulation, z-index management, and cleanup during unmount.

wiki_catalogs.name: Custom Elements
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive documentation for the customElement() API. Detail how it bridges Woby's reactive system with Web Components, including registration, attribute observation, and property binding. Explain the class implementation that extends HTMLElement with reactive props, shadow DOM integration, and stylesheet adoption. Document support for nested properties (using $ and . notation), style attribute handling, and automatic kebab-case to camelCase conversion. Cover the connectedCallback() lifecycle, attributeChangedCallback1() for reactive updates, and disconnectedCallback() cleanup. Include examples of defining and using custom elements in both HTML and JSX. Address SSR considerations, type safety with ElementAttributes, and integration with Woby's observable system.

wiki_catalogs.name: Testing Rendering
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create detailed documentation for Woby's testing renderer in render.testing.ts. Explain how the render() function creates an isolated DOM environment for unit testing components. Document the returned testing utilities: getByRole, getByTestId, and getByText, including their type signatures and usage patterns. Describe the internal setup with temporary div elements, fragment management, and automatic attachment to document.body. Provide practical examples of testing component output, event handling, and state changes. Explain the unmount function and disposal mechanism for cleanup after tests. Address integration with testing frameworks like Jest or Vitest, and discuss best practices for avoiding memory leaks in test suites.

wiki_catalogs.name: Shadow DOM and Style Encapsulation
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for Shadow DOM integration in Woby custom elements. Explain how the constructor attaches a shadow root with open mode and serializable option, creating encapsulated DOM trees. Document the stylesheet adoption mechanism that automatically applies global styles to custom elements through convertAllDocumentStylesToConstructed and observeStylesheetChanges utilities. Cover the ignoreStyle prop that allows opt-out of global style adoption and its use cases for truly isolated components. Explain the module-level stylesheet observation that ensures efficient style updates across all custom elements. Include examples of styling custom elements with CSS custom properties and address common issues like style conflicts, performance considerations with many custom elements, and debugging style application problems.

wiki_catalogs.name: Hooks API
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the Hooks API section focused on Woby's reactivity hooks system. Explain how hooks differ from React by not requiring dependency arrays and allowing conditional calling. Document state management hooks like useState equivalents using observables. Cover side effect hooks (useEffect), resource loading (useResource), and timing functions (useTimeout, useInterval). Explain the implementation details from the source files, including how use_render_effect.ts handles rendering effects. Provide practical examples showing hook composition and nesting. Address common patterns and anti-patterns. Include performance considerations and debugging tips for hook usage.

wiki_catalogs.name: Context and Lifecycle
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the Context and Lifecycle sub-feature focused on component lifecycle and dependency injection in Woby. Explain how use_context enables reactive context propagation without re-renders, and how it differs from React's context API. Document use_mounted and use_mounted_context for detecting component attachment and managing lifecycle-dependent logic. Include examples of theme providers, authentication contexts, and nested context scenarios. Address common issues like context unavailability during SSR and provide solutions. Highlight performance benefits of Woby's direct DOM updates in context propagation and best practices for avoiding unnecessary context updates.

wiki_catalogs.name: Suspense
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop comprehensive content for Woby's Suspense component. Explain its role in handling asynchronous operations like data fetching, code splitting, and resource loading with fallback UIs. Document the internal architecture including SuspenseContext, SuspenseManager, and SuspenseCollector for coordinating suspense states across component trees. Show usage patterns with useResource and lazy components. Provide examples of nested suspense boundaries and fallback stacking. Explain how Wobys signal-based reactivity integrates with suspension by throwing promises and resuming when resolved. Address SSR implications, including streaming support and shell rendering. Discuss performance trade-offs and best practices for avoiding excessive fallbacks. Include debugging techniques and common issues such as infinite loading states or missing boundary definitions.

wiki_catalogs.name: Context and Dependency Injection Hooks
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for Woby's context and dependency injection hooks. Explain use_context for consuming values from a React-like context system with strong typing and default value support. Cover use_guarded for conditional context access with fallback behaviors. Document use_assigned_slot for detecting assigned slot content in custom elements. Provide examples of theme propagation, service injection, and nested component communication. Address common issues like context invalidation, provider hierarchy, and type safety. Demonstrate integration with create_context and proper disposal patterns. Highlight how Woby's context system works seamlessly with SSR and custom elements.

wiki_catalogs.name: Suspense
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the Suspense component. Explain its role in gracefully handling asynchronous operations such as data fetching, code splitting, and resource loading by displaying fallback content while waiting. Document the 'fallback' prop and how Woby's useResource hook integrates with Suspense to signal pending states. Describe the internal architecture using SuspenseContext for parent-child coordination, SuspenseManager for tracking pending resources, and SuspenseCollector for batch resolution. Cover hydration behavior during SSR and streaming support. Provide examples of lazy-loaded routes, image galleries with loading placeholders, and form data preloading. Address common issues like infinite fallback loops, nested suspense boundaries, and timeout strategies. Highlight performance benefits of progressive rendering and reduced perceived load times.

wiki_catalogs.name: Lazy Loading
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed documentation for the lazy() function and code splitting capabilities. Explain how it enables asynchronous component loading with Suspense integration. Document the fetcher function pattern, resource management via useResource(), and the preload() method for proactive loading. Cover the implementation across browser, SSR, and via.js environments, including how each handles promise resolution and component resolution. Provide examples of lazy-loading route components, UI elements, and third-party integrations. Address error handling, loading states, and performance benefits of code splitting. Include best practices for bundle optimization and preload strategies in different application architectures.

wiki_catalogs.name: Type Conversion and Serialization
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for type conversion and serialization in Woby custom elements. Explain how setObservableValue handles automatic type conversion between string attributes and JavaScript values based on observable options (number, boolean, bigint, object). Document the fromHtml and toHtml serialization options that enable custom conversion logic for complex types like Dates and Objects. Cover the pattern of storing functions in arrays with toHtml: () => undefined to prevent exposure in HTML attributes. Explain how JSON.stringify/JSON.parse are used for object serialization and ISO string conversion for dates. Include practical examples of custom serialization strategies and address common issues like circular references, precision loss with numbers, and timezone handling with dates.

wiki_catalogs.name: Rendering
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the rendering section focused on Woby's rendering system. Explain browser rendering implementation in render.ts, including the rendering pipeline and DOM updates. Document server-side rendering capabilities in render.ssr.ts and the ssr/ directory, covering hydration and streaming considerations. Explain testing rendering in render.testing.ts and integration with testing frameworks. Compare the different rendering targets (SSR, VIA, browser) and their implementation differences. Provide practical examples showing render() usage patterns. Address performance optimization techniques and common rendering issues. Include guidance on choosing the appropriate rendering method for different use cases.

wiki_catalogs.name: Event and DOM Hooks
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the Event and DOM Hooks sub-feature focused on DOM interaction in Woby. Explain how use_event_listener safely manages event subscriptions with automatic cleanup. Document use_assigned_slot for working with Shadow DOM and web components, including practical examples of slot-based layouts. Cover use_scheduler for coordinating DOM updates with the browser's rendering cycle. Include usage patterns for keyboard navigation, drag-and-drop, and custom event systems. Address common issues like event delegation, memory leaks from orphaned listeners, and timing conflicts with rendering. Provide performance optimization tips for high-frequency events and batch DOM operations.

wiki_catalogs.name: Error Boundaries
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create detailed documentation for the ErrorBoundary component in Woby. Explain its purpose in catching JavaScript errors during rendering, logging them, and displaying a fallback UI instead of crashing the entire app. Document its props such as 'fallback' and error handling lifecycle. Provide examples showing integration with observables and recovery mechanisms like retrying failed renders. Explain how it works under the hood using try-catch around component execution and integration with Wobys rendering scheduler. Address limitations, such as not catching asynchronous errors or event handlers, and suggest complementary strategies. Include best practices for error logging, user feedback, and graceful degradation. Discuss SSR considerations where errors must be captured synchronously and rendered appropriately.

wiki_catalogs.name: Abort Control and Cancellation Hooks
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for Woby's abort control hooks. Explain use_abort_controller for creating AbortController instances that are automatically disposed when components unmount. Cover use_abort_signal for deriving AbortSignal instances from the component's cancellation token. Provide examples of canceling fetch requests, WebSocket connections, and long-running computations. Demonstrate integration with use_fetch and other async hooks. Address common scenarios like route changes, user cancellations, and resource cleanup. Highlight how these hooks prevent memory leaks and ensure operations don't complete on unmounted components.

wiki_catalogs.name: Error Boundary
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the ErrorBoundary component. Explain its purpose in catching JavaScript errors during rendering, lifecycle methods, or in constructors of child components, preventing the entire app from crashing. Document the 'fallback' render function that receives error and reset props, enabling graceful recovery with retry mechanisms. Describe how it leverages Woby's reactive system to isolate error states and allow resumable rendering after reset. Cover usage patterns such as logging errors, displaying user-friendly messages, and fallback UIs for broken components. Provide examples in dynamic imports, third-party widget integration, and complex form handling. Address limitations including inability to catch async errors, event handlers, or errors in the boundary itself. Recommend best practices for placement and error monitoring integration.

wiki_catalogs.name: Server-Side Rendering
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive documentation for Woby's server-side rendering capabilities through renderToString(). Explain the asynchronous version for browser-like environments with Suspense support, and the synchronous SSR implementation for server contexts. Document the rendering pipeline that captures component output into string format, including portal handling and hydration considerations. Cover the use of SuspenseCollector for tracking pending resources and the disposer pattern for cleanup. Provide examples of generating HTML for HTTP responses, static site generation, and pre-rendering workflows. Address streaming SSR possibilities, error handling during server rendering, and performance optimization for high-throughput scenarios.

wiki_catalogs.name: Utilities
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the utilities section focused on Woby's helper functions. Explain class management in classlist.ts, including support for arrays, objects, and reactive class expressions. Document style handling in stylesheets.ts and setters.ts, covering CSS property manipulation and style merging. Explain DOM manipulation utilities and their role in direct DOM updates. Cover advanced nested property support in nested.ts that enables setting deeply nested properties through HTML attributes. Provide practical examples showing complex class expressions and style bindings. Address performance considerations and best practices for using these utilities effectively in components.

wiki_catalogs.name: Fragments
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the Fragment component in Woby. Explain its role in grouping multiple elements without adding extra DOM nodes, essential for clean markup and efficient rendering. Document its implementation and how it integrates with the JSX transformer and rendering engine. Provide usage examples with both short syntax (<></>) and explicit <Fragment> tags. Explain how fragments are handled during SSR and hydration, especially when adjacent text nodes or comments are involved. Discuss performance benefits and compatibility with directives or event listeners. Address common issues such as inability to apply attributes or keys directly to fragments, and suggest workarounds. Include guidance on when to use fragments versus wrapper divs based on styling and layout needs.

wiki_catalogs.name: Advanced Features
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the advanced features section focused on Woby's sophisticated capabilities. Explain custom elements implementation in custom_element.ts, including reactive properties and integration with web components. Document the Context API in create_context.tsx and use_context.ts, covering provider-consumer patterns and scoping. Explain advanced nested property support that allows setting deeply nested properties through HTML attributes using $ and . notation. Provide practical examples showing custom element registration and context usage. Address integration patterns between these features and performance implications. Include guidance on when to use these advanced features and common implementation challenges.

wiki_catalogs.name: Keep Alive
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create detailed documentation for the KeepAlive component in Woby. Explain its purpose in preserving component state and DOM structure when components are unmounted and remounted, useful for tab interfaces or navigation caches. Document how it works internally by detaching the DOM subtree from the document but keeping it alive in memory. Provide examples showing state retention across visibility toggles and integration with routing systems. Discuss memory management trade-offs and when to avoid KeepAlive due to resource constraints. Include cleanup strategies, manual ejection APIs, and SSR limitations where state cannot be preserved across requests.

wiki_catalogs.name: Integration
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for the integration section focused on Woby's ecosystem integrations. Explain JSX support through the jsx/ directory and jsx-runtime.js, including runtime configuration and compiler directives. Document Via.js integration in the via/ directory and via.js, covering alternative rendering targets and use cases. Explain SSR integration through src/ssr/ and ssr.js, including server-side rendering setup and considerations. Address the differences between various implementation files (e.g., .ssr.ts, .via.ts). Provide practical examples showing JSX usage and integration with different rendering engines. Include configuration options and performance considerations for each integration point.

wiki_catalogs.name: API Reference
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive API documentation for Woby's public interfaces. Document core methods from methods/index.ts including render, createElement, h, and customElement with their signatures, parameters, and return values. Cover components API from components/index.ts, detailing props and behavior. Document hooks API from hooks/index.ts, explaining each hook's purpose and usage patterns. Include type definitions from types.ts, covering interfaces like Component, Child, and Props. Provide practical examples for each API endpoint showing common usage patterns. Address versioning, deprecation policies, and backward compatibility. Include code snippets from the actual implementation to illustrate edge cases and advanced usage.

wiki_catalogs.name: Best Practices
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the best practices section focused on optimal usage patterns for Woby. Explain recommended approaches for state management, effect handling, and component design. Document performance optimization techniques like avoiding unnecessary useMemo and proper effect cleanup. Cover anti-patterns to avoid, such as React-style dependency arrays and manual dependency tracking. Explain the differences from React patterns as outlined in Woby-vs-React.md. Make content accessible to beginners while providing sufficient technical depth for experienced developers.

wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive migration guide content focused on transitioning from React to Woby. Document the key differences in reactivity models, explaining how observable-based reactivity replaces useState and useEffect. Provide direct comparisons between React patterns and Woby equivalents for state management, effects, and rendering. Cover type conversion strategies from React types to Woby types as detailed in React-to-Woby-Type-Conversion.md. Explain how to refactor common React patterns like conditional rendering and list mapping to use Woby components. Address mindset shifts required for automatic dependency tracking and no VDOM architecture. Include practical examples showing code transformations. Provide troubleshooting guidance for common migration challenges.

wiki_catalogs.name: Examples
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive examples content focused on practical implementations of Woby features. Document complete application examples like the Todo App from the README, explaining each component and hook usage. Cover various demo applications including counters, clocks, and interactive UIs. wiki_overview.content:
<blog>
# Comprehensive Project Analysis of Woby Framework

## 1. Project Introduction

### Purpose Statement
Woby is a high-performance JavaScript framework designed for building rich web applications with fine-grained observable/signal-based reactivity. The framework provides a lightweight, efficient solution for reactive UI development with support for server-side rendering, custom elements, and various rendering targets.

### Core Goals and Objectives
- Deliver high-performance reactive UI capabilities through fine-grained observables
- Support multiple rendering environments (browser, SSR, via.js integration)
- Provide a comprehensive set of UI components and hooks for common patterns
- Enable seamless integration with custom elements and web components
- Offer type-safe, reactive programming model with automatic attribute synchronization

### Target Audience
- Frontend developers building reactive web applications
- Library authors creating reusable UI components
- Teams requiring high-performance UI frameworks with small bundle sizes
- Developers working with custom elements and web components
- Projects needing both client-side and server-side rendering capabilities

## 2. Technical Architecture

### Component Breakdown
The Woby framework is organized into several core modules that work together to provide a complete reactive UI solution:

```mermaid
graph TD
    A[Woby Framework] --> B[Core Components]
    A --> C[Reactivity System]
    A --> D[Rendering Engine]
    A --> E[JSX Integration]
    A --> F[Utility Functions]
    
    B --> B1[Dynamic Components]
    B --> B2[Conditional Rendering]
    B --> B3[Suspense Management]
    B --> B4[Portals]
    
    C --> C1[Observable State]
    C --> C2[Hooks System]
    C --> C3[Context Management]
    
    D --> D1[Browser Rendering]
    D --> D2[SSR Rendering]
    D --> D3[Testing Rendering]
    D --> D4[Via.js Integration]
    
    E --> E1[JSX Runtime]
    E --> E2[Element Creation]
    E --> E3[Template Processing]
    
    F --> F1[DOM Manipulation]
    F --> F2[Type Utilities]
    F --> F3[Diffing Algorithms]
```

### Design Patterns
Woby implements several key design patterns:

- **Observable/Signal Pattern**: Fine-grained reactivity through observable values
- **Component Composition**: Reusable UI components built from smaller primitives
- **Dependency Injection**: Context system for sharing state across component trees
- **Factory Pattern**: Element creation through `createElement` functions
- **Decorator Pattern**: Enhanced components through `wrapElement` and `wrapCloneElement`
- **Strategy Pattern**: Different implementations for various rendering targets (SSR, via, browser)

### System Relationships
The framework's architecture demonstrates clear separation of concerns with well-defined relationships between components:

```mermaid
graph LR
    JSX[JSX Syntax] --> CR[Create Element]
    CR --> RE[Rendering Engine]
    RE --> DOM[DOM Manipulation]
    
    Hooks[Hooks System] --> RS[Reactivity System]
    RS --> OBS[Observables]
    
    Components[UI Components] --> HU[Hook Usage]
    HU --> RS
    
    CE[Custom Elements] --> CT[Component Types]
    CT --> CR
    
    SSR[Server-Side Rendering] --> REND[Render Functions]
    REND --> HTML[HTML Output]
    
    OBS --> RE
    CT --> RE
```

### Data Flow Diagram
The data flow in Woby follows a unidirectional pattern with reactive updates:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[User Input] --> B[Event Handler]
    B --> C[State Update]
    C --> D[Observable Change]
    D --> E[Dependency Tracking]
    E --> F[Component Re-evaluation]
    F --> G[DOM Update]
    G --> H[UI Render]
    
    I[External Data] --> J[Resource Fetch]
    J --> K[Observable Update]
    K --> D
    
    L[Props Change] --> M[Component Re-render]
    M --> F
```

## 3. Key Implementation

### Main Entry Points
- [index.ts](src/index.ts): Primary export file that aggregates all framework components
- [jsx-runtime.ts](src/jsx-runtime.ts): JSX runtime implementation
- [ssr.ts](src/ssr.ts): Server-side rendering entry point
- [via.ts](src/via.ts): Via.js integration entry point
- [testing.ts](src/testing.ts): Testing utilities entry point

### Core Modules
- [methods](src/methods): Core framework methods including rendering, element creation, and state management
- [components](src/components): Pre-built UI components for common patterns
- [hooks](src/hooks): Reactivity hooks for state management and side effects
- [utils](src/utils): Utility functions for DOM manipulation, type checking, and diffing
- [jsx](src/jsx): JSX-related functionality and runtime implementation

### Configuration Approach
- [package.json](package.json): Project metadata, dependencies, and build scripts
- [tsconfig.json](tsconfig.json): TypeScript configuration for compilation
- [vite.config.ts](not shown): Build configuration (inferred from package.json scripts)

### External Dependencies

## 4. Key Features

### Functionality Overview
Woby provides a comprehensive set of features for building reactive web applications:

- Fine-grained reactivity system based on observables/signals
- JSX support with custom runtime
- Server-side rendering capabilities
- Integration with via.js for alternative rendering
- Comprehensive set of UI components for common patterns
- Hooks system for state management and side effects
- Custom elements support with type synchronization
- Testing utilities for component testing
- Hot module replacement support

### Implementation Highlights
- [render.ts](src/methods/render.ts): Browser rendering implementation
- [render.ssr.ts](src/methods/render.ssr.ts): Server-side rendering implementation
- [render.via.ts](src/methods/render.via.ts): Via.js rendering implementation
- [createElement.ts](src/methods/create_element.ts): Element creation with support for multiple component types
- [create_element.ssr.ts](src/methods/create_element.ssr.ts): SSR-specific element creation
- [create_element.via.ts](src/methods/create_element.via.ts): Via.js-specific element creation
- [constants.ts](src/constants.ts): Framework-wide constants and symbols
- [types.ts](src/types.ts): Comprehensive type definitions for the framework

```mermaid
    Components --> Context: Shared context
    
    State --> Update: State changes
    Effects --> DOM: DOM updates
    Context --> Propagation: Context propagation
    
    Update --> Re-render: Component re-evaluation
    Re-render --> DOM
    
    DOM --> [*]

    HTML --> [*]

    ViaDOM --> [*]
```
